前的事情了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以这很有趣，因为有一段时间，我们所说的耶鲁模型，真正是大卫·斯文森的天才，是他在替代品还很小的时候就很早就采用了，它们大多表现出色，有很多阿尔法一代，这不是一个可以钓鱼的大池塘，而耶鲁大学的模型却表现得非常出色。捐赠基金的驱动因素是什么？如果不是表现不佳，那么，肯定比我们在 80 年代、90 年代和 2000 年代初看到的表现更差。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我的意思是，我对你所说的唯一警告是我不确定你是否正确测量了它，性能更差。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：哦不，情况更糟。</p><p> SEIDES：更低。更低了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：好的，这很公平。</p><p> SEIDES：但市场回报——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：过去十年，2010年到2020年，我们是什么？ 14、一年15%？</p><p> SEIDES：如果标准普尔指数是你的基准，那么它不适用于这些资本池。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们的基准应该是什么？顺便说一句，这是一个非常公平的观点。您是全球投资者。也许标准普尔并不是最好的选择。</p><p>赛德斯：是的，没错。我的意思是，大卫·斯文森 (David Swensen) 的早期创新信念之一是，如果你管理的资本池实际上是一个永久的时间范围。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：无限，对吧？</p><p> SEIDES：你想要深思熟虑的多元化。因此，如果您从标准普尔 500 指数开始，或者在本例中是股票和债券，那么您只有两种资产类别，对吧。问题是，如果你能找到其他投资领域，能够产生你的负债流所需的回报类型，多元化就成为免费午餐。</p><p>因此，这些资金池的正确基准必须看起来有点像他们投资的基础资产。</p><p>里索兹：很公平。那么你用什么作为基准呢？现在请记住，让我们以大卫投资的项目为例。当然有股票和债券，但也有房地产。在人们还不知道之前就已经有了商品。等等，木头？我们为什么投资木材？然后是风险投资、私人信贷和对冲基金。</p><p>那么，如何为看起来与 60/40 分配完全不同的分配创建基准呢？</p><p> SEIDES：嗯，你必须考虑一下你想要衡量的是什么。因此，正如您所说，一个合理的基准可能是 60/40 或 70/30。这是一个非常容易创建的投资组合。可以肯定的是，在过去的 10 年、15 年里，它是很难被击败的。</p><p>从较长一段时间来看，也许不会那么多。</p><p>如果您查看耶鲁大学投资的资产类型，您可以为每个池创建一个基准。这允许您做两件事。一般来说，它可以让您了解整个投资组合的合理贝塔值是多少。它允许你做的另一件事是衡量你选择在每个领域和整个袖子上都表现出色的经理的能力。</p><p>所以你可以想象在房地产领域，有一个你可以使用的净租赁房地产指数。您也可以使用房地产投资信托基金指数，尽管它在私人市场上有所不同。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：您可以使用风险投资和私募股权方面的纯粹基准，然后您可以将各个资产类别的基准进行汇总，以获得整个池的基准。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：真的很有趣。所以耶鲁模式全盛时期以来发生了两个问题，一是大家都在模仿耶鲁模式。所以第一个问题是，这是否会给想要遵循耶鲁模式的分配者带来挑战？它不再是，“嘿，我自己拥有了整个领域。我还有 500 个其他捐赠基金、基金会和机构试图参与进来——试图在这个池塘里钓鱼。”</p><p> SEIDES：是的，确实如此。我认为，当你思考耶鲁模型时，它有助于理解大卫的想法，而不是你给耶鲁模型贴上的标签及其含义。</p><p>大卫的才华之一是他从第一原则开始做一切事情。有什么意义呢？您对世界和投资有什么信念？那么你如何以严格的纪律来应用它呢？</p><p>他在他的书中写到了这一点，人们看到后会说：“哦，我可以复制它。”但大多数人都很难拥有自己的信念，并在执行方面遇到困难时坚持自己的信念。</p><p>大卫拥有的另一点无人能真正复制的是对持续改进的坚定信念和令人难以置信的远见，既能看到大机会，就像你可以想象很久以前的对冲基金一样，也能看到小机会。因此，他在 35、40 年前就先于其他人考虑了收费问题，以及何时可以对此采取行动。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：就是他和杰克·博格尔，仅此而已。</p><p>赛德斯：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：考虑费用。这样做的缺点是，我要借用吉姆·查诺斯的话，他谈到 Kynikos Associates 著名的卖空者时说，“在 80 年代，有 500 家对冲基金。他们都产生了阿尔法。现在有 11,000 家对冲基金，其中 500 家正在创造阿尔法收益。”所以另一个挑战是如何从11,000个对冲基金和10,000个风险基金以及天知道有多少私募股权基金和私募信贷基金中进行选择，使得配置内的选择似乎变得更加困难，更多复杂，即使你找到了你真正喜欢的基金经理，你现在也正在与其他有限合伙人竞争将你的十亿美元投入那里。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，这是绝对正确的，根据资产类别，有不同的镜头组。但仅以多头空头股权投资为例，您要问的第一个问题是，这是您想要的地方吗？</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：因为这是一场更加艰难的比赛，特别是在空头方面比以前增加了价值。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：做空一直很困难。有这样一个神话：人们先建立空头头寸，然后谈论它，然后数钱。这比那要困难得多。</p><p>赛德斯：是的。所以我认为在任何资产类别中选择管理者都需要这两点。那么我们回到大卫的首要原则，你认为哪种类型的经理应该表现出色？有些人认为，与那些比其他人更了解自己业务的人进行基本自由裁量投资是正确的做法。</p><p>还有其他人认为，“不，你需要像 Citadel 或 Millennium 那样规模庞大、系统化。”没有对错之分，但您必须遵循自己的一套信念，以确保您认为对您的泳池有用。</p><p>另一方面，比如你提到的风险投资，访问确实很重要。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：这就是你可以看到耶鲁大学并说他们在 30 年前就拥有先发优势的地方。他们已经是顶级风险投资经理，不从任何人那里拿钱。有很多投资者说，我在播客上说，“如果我们无法进入那些顶级风险投资，”你就没有风险投资的分配，你有一群经理。 And you take what you can get, but you don&#39;t extend beyond what you believe are the very top tier because the dispersion returns in that asset class is really wide and you only want to be in, say, that top core top.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So we&#39;ll circle back to this podcast thing you referenced later because I&#39;m interested in that. But I love the idea of the first mover advantage.</p><p> When you think about the Yale model, when Swensen was first allocating to these other asset types, commodities, lands, alternatives, it was the Wild West. It was wide open. How much of an advantage did he have being a pioneer in those spaces? The old joke is, “Yeah, yeah, the second mouse gets the cheese.” In this case, it looks like the first mouse got the cheese.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, it was shooting fish in a barrel.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really?</p><p> SEIDES: When I worked at Yale, the hardest part of the game was understanding that the game was getting played, knowing where to go to access it, and then on top of that, having your board approval to let you do it.</p><p> So to give you some examples of that, I joined Yale in &#39;92, David was there in &#39;85.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: There were some venture investments when they got there. It wasn&#39;t a full thing, but they loved it. They quickly understood the potential for that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Who, the board?</p><p> SEIDES: No, Yale, David and Dean Takashi, the team at Yale.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But did the oversight, the governance get it?</p><p> SEIDES: They were already in place. They really did.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Okay.</p><p> SEIDES: And that&#39;s a huge aspect of Yale&#39;s success.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: No doubt about it.</p><p> SEIDES: The success of that governance. So they then had time to go to Silicon Valley to meet with the people, to see over a decade who was good and who wasn&#39;t, to ask questions and to make mistakes. That&#39;s a huge first mover advantage.</p><p> By the time I got there in &#39;92, they had a great venture portfolio and almost nobody else even understood what venture capital was.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It was just starting to ramp up &#39;93, &#39;94, &#39;95, and by late &#39;90s, everyone had been piling in. If you&#39;re there a decade before, talk about first mover. Oh my goodness.</p><p> SEIDES: And hedge funds were the same way. To give you a fun story, we launched Protégé Partners in 2002. In that period of time, &#39;92 to &#39;02, you really had a golden era of hedge funds in terms of returns.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: The whole pre-financial crisis decade or two, hedge funds crushed-crushed it. Or at least the top, pick a number, 30, 40%. Less, 20, 30%?</p><p> SEIDES: I know back then, the premier job in asset management was to run Fidelity Magellan. There was no reason to think people would make billions of dollars running hedge funds. It was such a boutique industry. I used to say that the guys who ran hedge funds were the one who woke up on the wrong side of the bed in the morning and felt like they just had to short because things were going wrong.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGH)</p><p> SEIDES: So when we launched Protégé, we had a classification of hedge funds and said we&#39;re going to not invest in the large ones. And in 2002, the bucket of the largest hedge funds was those north of $1 billion.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: And then I started reaching out to some of the managers I knew from my time at Yale, and one of them said to me, “We&#39;re closed. We have a wait list.” And I said, “What is that?” He said, “I don&#39;t know.” But all of a sudden, people have said, “Why don&#39;t you start a wait list?”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: We&#39;re at a capacity and that&#39;s that.</p><p> SEIDES: Before 2002, there were no capacity issues with whoever you thought the best hedge funds were.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And subsequently, there&#39;s been some academic research that has implied, I don&#39;t want to say found, but strongly implied that much, and again, much not most, of the alpha is coming from the emerging managers.</p><p> SEIDES: So that was the premise of the business we started at Protege. And I would tell you that while true that academic research, it&#39;s all deeply flawed. All of this.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Well, there&#39;s a little hindsight bias built in, right?</p><p> SEIDES: There&#39;s hindsight bias. The data of the managers you really want to measure isn&#39;t included in that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It&#39;s all self-reported, right?</p><p> SEIDES: And then I&#39;ve never seen a study who said that the large managers were anything north of 50 million in assets, the large managers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What?</p><p> SEIDES: So you look at those studies, they say the small ones are less than 5 million.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Million or billion? Are we talking about the- a typo, it sounds like. Because if you look at Millennium and Citadel and Oak Tree and AQR, which just had a fantastic year, and Bridgewater, we&#39;re talking 50, 100, 150 billion dollars. These are massive pools of capital.</p><p> SEIDES: The problem is the academics who do the research don&#39;t have access to the performance data of the funds that matter.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: None of them are, call it, asset weighted. And so those studies, while true, And while they seem to have an intellectual vigor to them in thought process, they&#39;re really not based on anything in the real world of the investment market.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So all of this tees up the obvious question. Was Warren Buffett right? Are most people better off in an index fund than playing with an active manager, be it mutual fund or high fee hedge funds?</p><p> SEIDES: John Yeah, I said back then, the bet started in 2007 and I say today, being in the market and investing in hedge funds is completely apples and oranges. So for a taxable investor, hedge funds generally aren&#39;t tax efficient. And when you look at the assets that are invested, the three trillion in hedge funds, I would guess that north of 90% of that are in institutions that don&#39;t pay taxes.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: David So foundations, endowments.</p><p> SEIDES: So as an individual, it probably doesn&#39;t make sense, generally speaking.</p><p> As an institution, it has a very different risk return profile that when done well, fits in really well with the diversified portfolio that we&#39;ve talked about earlier.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You have to tell us, where did the idea come from? How did you reach out to Buffett? And what was his response?</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. Well, and you have to go back. This is the summer of 2007.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: 2007. So, let me set the table a little bit. You had the run up in the dot coms to 2000. I have a vivid recollection of people saying, “Ah, Buffett&#39;s old. He&#39;s lost his touch,” right? Then everything implodes and again, Buffett is outperforming for a while. Post October lows in &#39;02, March double bottom &#39;03, the invasion of Iraq. By the time you get to &#39;07, market&#39;s up 80, 90% from the lows and housing is just about peaking and things are starting to come apart around then. By &#39;07, it&#39;s pretty clear that the housing bears are going to be right.</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s right. So I had seen that Warren had made a comment to a bun