的是我们每年都会出去和他一起吃晚饭。</p><p>里索兹：来吧。那价值一百万美元。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我会和我的合作伙伴一起去，我们可能会带上我们的一位经理或亲密的朋友。</p><p>里索兹： 三又四分之一。那值三又四分之一，哦，天啊，谈便宜了。</p><p> SEIDES：所以各种各样的事情都由此而来。举个例子，我带出来的一个人名叫史蒂夫·加尔布雷斯。他曾任摩根士丹利首席策略师。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Sure.</p><p> SEIDES：他在职业上与杰克·博格尔是最好的朋友。我把史蒂夫带出来。史蒂夫对沃伦说：“你想让杰克参加你的年会吗？”沃伦点亮了。他是我的偶像之一。这导致沃伦宣布打赌时杰克也在场。这是他第一次参加年会。距他去世还有一两年。所以你把他带到那里，所有的一切都是那天晚上和沃伦一起吃晚饭的结果。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他什么时候去世的？我想那是2015年。对。</p><p>所以，所以他宣布了他，那么沃伦是什么时候在08年或09年他让他在，在，还是很久以后？</p><p> SEIDES：不，那是很久以后的事了。</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p>赛德斯：那是很久以后的事情了。</p><p>里索兹：哦，是的。一定是在几次之后——</p><p> SEIDES：我想那是在他 90 岁生日前后。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.他的声音仍然令人惊叹，有点驼背，但充满力量和智慧。我们在他这个年纪都应该如此敏锐。</p><p>所以，这是一个愚蠢的问题，但我必须问。那么，公司花费了 320,000 美元，每一分钱都值得吗？或者，对我来说，这听起来整件事都很壮观。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我不会用经济回报来衡量。就像，我不认为——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：不，不，我的意思是全面的。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，作为一种经历和人际关系，这真是非同寻常。沃伦是——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：独一无二。</p><p> SEIDES：他是货真价实的人。</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> SEIDES：他从来都不需要和我们一起吃晚饭。真是太有趣了。他讲的故事，我们听了很多，但是一遍又一遍地听到不同的故事，投资故事，非投资故事，他真的很了不起。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这是一个疯狂的问题，我再次觉得有必要问这个问题。难道这个被称为世界上最伟大的投资者的家伙，无论这个头衔是否准确，都没关系。难不成他还是被低估了？因为每隔几年，人们就会开始站出来说：“啊，他失去了触觉，他们的表现并不出色。”然后他让人们感到惊讶。每十年，这种事似乎都会发生。</p><p> SEIDES：我的意思是，要让他被低估，你必须对他有一定程度的评价，对吗？我认为人们对他非常尊敬。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：有些人这样做，但我从一些人、一些年轻的宽客那里听到了这一点。好吧，当你看看回报序列时，巴菲特在 60 年代末和 70 年代表现得非常好，这就是表现出色的源泉，你最近为我做了什么？我认为他们有点忽视了大局。</p><p>赛德斯：是的，我同意你的观点。当我们与大卫·斯文森谈论耶鲁大学的座右铭时，你也可以说同样的话，对吧？克里夫·阿斯内斯（Cliff Asness）写了一篇文章，说沃伦所做的就是购买这些优质股票，如果你复制了这个策略，你就可以复制结果，这绝对是真的。除了50年前，你必须知道买优质股票。那真是太棒了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：差不多 60 年前了，对吧？这就是疯狂的部分。</p><p> SEIDES：不，我的意思是，我认为他是如此非凡。当你很幸运能和他一起度过很多时间时，他所说的每句话都充满智慧。大卫·斯文森（David Swenson）也是如此。我一生中只认识少数几个这样的人。</p><p>里索兹：我认为查理·芒格是另一位。</p><p>赛德斯：我不认识查理，但在我认识的人中，沃伦嘴里说的每一句话，无论什么话题，我都跟他谈到了 A-Rod 与洋基队签约的事情。从他嘴里说出来的一切，都充满了智慧。</p><p>里索兹：这很有趣。你知道，有一张关于复利的精彩图表显示，你知道，普通人，你在 30 多岁时开始积累一点钱，你的投资窗口大约是 40 到 68。所以，如果你幸运的话，你会得到 25， 30年。</p><p>巴菲特已经将近 60 年了，当你看到复利效应的曲棍球棒时，你会发现，在过去的 25 年里，大多数人都没有让自己的钱为他们工作，他从亿万富翁变成了十亿富翁，再到十亿富翁。亿万富翁，人们只是没有意识到复利的影响。这不仅仅是金钱，而是那些似乎只会成倍增加的洞察力和智慧。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我们的朋友摩根·豪塞尔（Morgan Housel）以一种优美的方式讲述了这个故事。是时候了，对吧？这既是出色的投资，也是时间。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么让我们回到日常工作，即分配器。分配者的赌注有什么好处？</p><p> SEIDES：我不知道是否有很多。我有自己的收获。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以你来了。我会告诉你我的。你告诉我你的。</p><p> SEIDES: Sure.其中之一是时间段确实很重要。</p><p>里索兹：当然。</p><p>不仅仅是特定的时间长度，而是特定的时间块。</p><p>赛德斯：绝对正确。另一方面，这是了解媒体如何运作的一次有趣的练习。</p><p>所以我会给你讲两个小故事。当我们发起这个赌注时，卡罗尔·卢米斯（Carol Loomis）写了一篇关于这个赌注的文章。那真是太棒了。</p><p>里索兹：她最终写了巴菲特的传记《跳舞上班》之类的。</p><p> SEIDES: Correct.她也把赌注写在了上面。她的作品有两页。我对她说：“你怎么样——你要写一篇关于这个小赌注的文章吗？”而且做得非常好。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：哦，这不是一个小赌注，但继续吧。</p><p> SEIDES：当时就是这样的感觉。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really?</p><p> SEIDES: Sure.</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你正在和沃伦·巴菲特打一百万美元的赌注。在上帝的绿色地球上，这怎么可能是一个小小的赌注呢？</p><p> SEIDES：嗯，这可能不是一个小赌注，但我不认为除了这个赌注之外还有其他故事。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：再说一遍，我事后的偏见是，这就像你职业生涯中的决定性时刻，它影响着你余生所做的一切。你就是那个和沃伦·巴菲特打赌的人。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我知道这可能会刻在我的墓碑上，但我感觉这并不是一个决定性的时刻。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这里没有虚假的谦虚，因为我可以从你的脸上看到，你并没有夸大其词。当时你就觉得，哦，这只是一个有趣的小事。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我有机会和沃伦一起做这件事。多么酷啊？</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p>赛德斯：就是这样。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：好吧，我想历史已经把它放大到了比当时感觉更严重的程度？</p><p> SEIDES：对我来说不是，但对其他人来说肯定如此。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Okay.</p><p> SEIDES：所以卡罗尔写了这篇文章，而且她所做的一切都做得非常出色。然后还附有大量媒体。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，我清楚地记得这一点。她是《福布斯》还是《财富》杂志？</p><p>赛德斯：财富。</p><p>里索兹：财富。</p><p> SEIDES：所以请记住，有关该赌注的唯一明确信息是在卡罗尔的两页文章中。</p><p>里索兹：然后呢？</p><p> SEIDES：所有其他的文章都与事实不准确。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.这是多样性。每一份都比上一份差。这就像玩电话一样。</p><p> SEIDES：这令人大开眼界。另一个是，有很多不同的方式可以解释回报流。他们可以谈论这个赌注，谈论任何投资经理。我以一种我认为有很多优点的方式剖析了所发生的事情。诸如短期回扣之类的事情，诸如选择标准普尔指数与全球指数之类的事情，各种各样的事情。事实上，我是在彭博社报道的。这是我的第一堂课，当时我不知道当你写一篇文章时，你无法控制文章的标题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：仅供参考，编辑写标题，作者写正文。</p><p> SEIDES: Correct.所以我写了一篇大约九年的文章，不管标题是什么“为什么我输掉了与沃伦·巴菲特的赌注”。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，这是点击诱饵，值得点击的人会使用它。</p><p> SEIDES：但是赌注还没有结束，所以它变成了一件有趣的事情。它也完全改变了我所写内容的基调。因为这让它看起来像是一系列借口，而不是分析。</p><p>里索兹：有比沃伦·巴菲特更糟糕的赌注输掉了。外卖是什么？整个令人愉悦的听起来体验对您有何影响？</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah.我还没有真正考虑过那么多。我的意思是，对我来说，最大的收获是人际关系的价值。我能够与沃伦共度时光，这是多么美妙、幸运的经历啊。为了了解，嗯，我认识的托德·库姆斯(Todd Combs)，还有特德·韦施勒(Ted Weschler)和特雷西·布里特·库尔(Tracy Britt Cool)，当时她在那里，他们都来参加这些晚宴，并且愉快地谈论市场投资。</p><p>所以，对我来说，这是无价的。你说：“赌注的价格是多少？”嗯，当沃伦第一次发起“捐赠誓言”时，我和沃伦一起做了一些事情，那段时光是无价的。有一次，没有人报名，他打电话说：“嘿，你认识其中一些对冲基金的人。有什么办法可以把他们围起来吗？”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：围捕一些人？让我们投入数十亿美元。</p><p> SEIDES：并试图做到这一点，并且有一两个人报名参加了这项工作。</p><p>里索兹：我可以告诉你一件事吗？你给某人打电话并说：“嘿，沃伦·巴菲特让我给你打电话。他签署了“捐赠誓言”。你愿意承诺捐钱吗？”顺便说一句，莱昂·库珀曼（Leon Cooperman）讲述了一个故事，当他签署“捐赠誓言”时，他去吃晚饭，是巴菲特，是比尔·盖茨，而且这个故事一直在继续。他不知道在这场与 12 个人的晚餐结束时，最新的人拿起支票并讲述了这个故事。他就像，我在环顾四周。每个人都比我富有五倍、十倍、二十倍。我被账单困住了，那些家伙点了昂贵的酒。</p><p>他讲述了这个故事。这很滑稽。你成功把沃伦介绍给一群对冲基金人士了吗？</p><p> SEIDES：是的，有两个人从中签约，这真是太棒了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我认为你放弃了沃伦的名字，这样的事情的大门就敞开了。</p><p>赛德斯：你知道，如果你坐拥十亿美元，我不确定你是否会因为沃伦的名字而放弃一半。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是其中一些人坐拥超过十亿美元的资产，为什么不呢？谁在乎？除非他们有自己的基础。我可以给你一份 30 位亿万富翁的名单。他们都建立了自己的基金会。这是他们自己税务规划的一部分。我喜欢巴菲特的想法。我不需要重复所有的努力和令人头痛的管理工作。让比尔去担心吧。 “比尔，我占一半。”</p><p>那么世界上最富有的两个人把盖茨基金会，实际上应该称为盖茨-巴菲特基金会，变成了这个巨人，它是什么，现在100多亿美元？也许不止于此。太棒了。总而言之，与沃伦·巴菲特的合作经历很好。</p><p> SEIDES：每个人都是赢家，尤其是慈善机构。我认为是 Girls Inc of Omaha，它是一个副业，我们下次再讨论，但最终它的金额超过了 200 万美元。正确的。就这么过去了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.他们的预算只是其中的一小部分，对吗？这简直让他们不知所措。我敢肯定。那太棒了。</p><p>那么让我们谈谈您的一些哲学和您的著作。我最喜欢你写的东西之一——你有一个播客。我们稍后会讨论这个问题。您向所有客人询问一个有关宠物烦恼的问题。我喜欢你的皮毛，我不知道，这是我最喜欢的皮毛之一。请告诉我们一些关于在概率世界中表达绝对性的投资者的故事。</p><p>告诉我们关于皮皮的事情，我不知道。</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah.嗯，我一直认为每个人都应该将投资视为一种概率游戏，而当你作为一名资金经理讲述故事以筹集资金时，发生的事情之一就是你需要表现出信念。最好的人可以将这种信念与谦逊结合起来，但有时你会发现人们说的话，这不仅仅是对生活的投资，他们只是确定会发生什么，这个、那个或其他事情的结果，但事实并非如此不可以那样工作。</p><p>因此，特别是现在，有很多事情要么是常识，要么是共识认为它们之间存在细微差别。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES：我看着它并说，“我不知道答案是什么。”现在你可以给它赋予概率权重，但我在这篇文章中介绍了一些不同的事情，我刚才说，“看，我不知道。”</p><p>里索兹：我喜欢这个。顺便说一句，如果你在电视上想让主持人头疼，让他们问你一个问题，只需说“我不知道”。</p><p> SEIDES：效果不太好。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们不知道该怎么办。他们看着你，就像在说：“你不知道是什么意思？”</p><p> SEIDES：它不适合制作非常好的电视节目。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这有助于制作诚实的电视节目，但这完全是另一回事。既然我们一直在谈论大卫·斯文森，那么让我们谈谈不要太短期。无论是机构投资还是个人投资，短期主义的问题有多大？</p><p> SEIDES：是的，这是一个巨大的问题，也是一个棘手的问题，因为激励系统在资产管理行业的运作方式，资本食物链上的每个人都在向其他人报告。</p><p>通过报告，人们必须创造绩效。因此，几十年来发生的情况是，每种投资的持有期限变得越来越短。问题是这是有成本的。</p><p>因此，在很多情况下，短期投资会付出长期回报的代价。</p><p>里索兹：真的很有趣。还有一句话让我很着迷。 “将回报评估仅限于当前的标记条件未能考虑到未来可能发生的各种可能性。”所以这是一个非常有内涵的声明。</p><p>它不仅充满了对近因效应的担忧，而且还讨论了所有可能结果范围的概率，没有是或否。这可能发生，那可能发生，这可能发生。告诉我们一些关于你是如何做到这一点的，而陷入当下对于长期回报来说是一个很大的问题。</p><p> SEIDES：嗯，如果你看看 SVB 发生的事情，就会发现资产负债表管理不善。所以你回到几年前，你可能会说，“那么，购买国债可以获得什么回报？”事实证明，如果你看看当时的市场，我会称之为 1%、五年期国债或十年期国债。所以你说：“好吧，我们需要投资。我们的存款成本低于此。我们将赚取利差，因此我们将以 1% 的利率进行投资。”</p><p>当然，问题在于，如果你说“未来 10 年可以获得多少回报”，而回报率为 1%，那么事实证明你错了，因为正确的做法是持有现金并等到利率升至 5%。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：尤其是当美联储表示“我们将在 21 世纪末、22 年初大幅加息”时。并不是他们没有传达这一点。</p><p> SEIDES: Correct.因此，如果你从较长的一段时间内审视这一点并说：“嗯，我的机会集不仅仅是今天可用的。这是今天可用的，明天也可能可用，我可以放弃短期内的一点点回报，在未来某个不可知的时间获得更高的回报。”这本来可以拯救 SVB。它本来可以拯救第一共和国。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：因此，将久期风险放在一边，但对于国债投资者来说，我知道您之前已经计算过。如果你在 2019 年、2021 年放弃 1% 的大脂肪产量，假设你放弃三年 1% 并得到零，那么接下来几年的数学如何运作？你会怎么做？</p><p> SEIDES：嗯，你做得好多了，对吧？所以甚至以五年为期限。你走一，一，一，一，一，或者零，零，零，五，五。</p><p>里索兹：遥遥领先。</p><p> SEIDES：你会得到更多。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.你遥遥领先。</p><p>所以人们往往会陷入当下而不去思考。所以我的描述是每个人都在处理照片，而他们应该处理一部电影或一部电影。</p><p>很难将自己从瞬间（这只是一个快照）中抽离出来，转而思考时间的弧线。这是人类大脑运作方式的一个缺陷，它甚至影响了专业投资者。</p><p> SEIDES：这是一个很好的类比。竞争也加剧了这种情况。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh, really?</p><p> SEIDES：所以，如果你是一名资金经理，你坐拥现金，收入为零，让我们简化一下例子，而街对面的人只赚一分钱，那么在这三年里，你的表现不佳。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，你正在损失现金。这就是永续资本的想法，你谈到的永续时间范围有时更理论化而不是现实，因为你可能没有10年、20年的负债，也没有永远不会归属的持续永续捐赠，但人们仍然生活在这个月里还有季度，谁在乎 1%？</p><p>好吧，分配者会看着你，而你在这三年里加入很糟糕。</p><p> SEIDES：资金管理行业面临着真正的挑战。所以就采用这个概念吧？人们对永久资本工具很感兴趣。事实证明，永久资本工具本身是无常的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES：您拥有以折扣价交易的封闭式基金，有时股东会施加开放式基金的压力。您的控股公司结构发生了管理层变动。然后在分配者社区中，这些永久资本池一般来说是由首席投资官管理的，他们的平均任期只有六年。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以不是那么永久。</p><p> SEIDES：毕竟不是那么永久。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我喜欢你写的一篇关于风险的文章中的这句话。 1998 年，您询问著名价值投资者迈克尔·普莱斯 (Michael Price)，他从投资 Sunbeam Corporation 中学到了什么，该公司由 Chainsaw Al Dunlap 经营，充斥着会计欺诈。整个事情最终崩溃了。他回应……</p><p> SEIDES：“绝对（脏话）什么都没有。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：对于那些正在收听广播的人来说，他的回答是：“绝对没有”，中间夹着一句脏话。你怎么能从那次经历中学到任何东西呢？告诉我们这一点。</p><p> SEIDES：挑战在于欺诈就是欺诈。因此，您在投资时就承担了风险。其中之一是你所做的所有分析都不是真实的。它的问题是，你可以使用 Madoff 作为一个例子，你可以使用 FTX 最近的一个例子，就是每 1% 或 2% 的分析时间，你都会试图弄清楚你所看到的是否是真实的，实施欺诈的人花费 100% 的时间领先于您。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.所以你写道，你花了 99% 的时间来评估交易的优点。估值是多少？从所有基本面来看，这种情况发生的可能性有多大。也许你会抛出 1% 的问题：“嘿，我看到的是真的吗？会不会有被骗的可能？”大多数时候你会说：“不，当然不是。伯尼·麦道夫是纳斯达克总裁。这怎么可能是诈骗呢？”正确的。普莱斯的这一承认令人惊讶。普通投资者的收获是什么？您可以采取什么措施来避免欺诈，还是这种情况永远存在？</p><p> SEIDES：有很多风险永远存在。欺诈是其中之一，但您可以通过多样化的方式远离它。因此，这体现在头寸规模和信念上，并确保你考虑到如果你在某件事上采取更集中的立场，所有可能出错的事情。</p><p>里索兹：真的很有趣。这是我喜欢的另一句话。卡尔·谢尔（Karl Scheer）表示：“如果治理结构不善，就不可能获得投资成功”。解释一下你的意思或者卡尔的意思。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，卡尔是辛辛那提大学的首席投资官。拥有首席投资官的分配池之上还有一个董事会。也许是一个投资委员会。该委员会通常最终负责做出投资决策。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这些板上都挤满了人。</p><p>赛德斯：是的，完全正确。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这似乎是根本问题，不是吗？</p><p> SEIDES：安妮·杜克（Annie Duke）在决策理论中谈到的所有内容，如果你作为董事会不能做出好的决定的话。我们称之为治理结构。实际的投资决策是如何做出的？你不可能有一个好的投资流程。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：她更注重过程而不是结果。你做出某些决定，即使它不起作用，你也必须坚持高概率，这又回到了你之前所说的，高概率的决定，即使它是失败者，从长远来看也是比运气好就赢了。</p><p>赛德斯：绝对正确。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：故事是这样的，我认为这是哈特福德投资，哈特福德保险公司。当他们聘请摩根士丹利作为外部顾问时，每个人都辞职了。整件事简直就是一场灾难。那里发生了什么？</p><p> SEIDES：这就是 Hartford HealthCare。大卫·霍姆格伦 (David Holmgren) 是首席信息官。</p><p> I can&#39;t say I know exactly what happened on the inside, but they had a team that had delivered a good track record. I&#39;m assuming there was some friction between that team and the board, and the board hired Morgan Stanley is an OCIO, not only without ever consulting the team, but they had an investment committee of knowledgeable experts, other endowment chief investment officers. That investment committee never knew that the board had done a search to replace the investment team.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Wow. That seems pretty egregious. Sounds like a bunch of personality conflicts and no organizational alpha. I&#39;m curious how has that investment pool done since this palace coup?</p><p> SEIDES: I don&#39;t know the answer. It&#39;s way too short of a period of time to actually have any assessment.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, right.</p><p> SEIDES: And on top of that, chances are the underlying investments were mostly the same as what they were before on the team.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So they were inheriting what happened. You know, I&#39;m reminded of what took place at Harvard with Larry Summers, I don&#39;t know, what was that, 15 years ago, 20 years ago? And they went from an absolute bone crusher, outperformer, alpha generator to just stinking up the joint for decades. It&#39;s hard to look at those changes, which by the way, didn&#39;t come from Summers. It came from an alumni who said, “Why are we spending all this money?” Even though they really were spending not a lot, especially once you looked at the returns. Talk about terrible governance destroying a beautiful, fragile, winning investment team.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. The compensation structures of the largest, most influential pools of the capital in the United States in particular are really challenged. Public pension funds that manage hundreds of billion dollars can be manned by professionals that make $80 to $150,000 a year. And you compare that with models that we&#39;ve seen in Canada and Australia where the investment professionals on those teams are market competitively compensated, maybe a slight discount to the market.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But not like 10%, not giant.</p><p> SEIDES: Exactly right. And in the US, these largest pools of capital might have 90% discounts to the market.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really? That&#39;s unbelievable. Listen, just paying up for something doesn&#39;t guarantee that you&#39;re going to get the best, but paying a 90% discount pretty much guarantees that you&#39;re in the bottom, let&#39;s call it half, I&#39;m being generous, probably quartile, that there&#39;s, you know, it&#39;s a market-based system. Don&#39;t you want the best people steering your $42 billion endowment? It&#39;s just so short-sighted.</p><p> Just goes to show you how important governance is. And since we&#39;re talking about governance, let&#39;s talk about another thing you had written that I was intrigued by. “What&#39;s in a name, the problem with ESG?” Now, we&#39;re not talking about wokeism or the political backlash, which is really a partisan political debate, what&#39;s the problem with ESG as a approach to value-based investing?</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. Well, let&#39;s start with the name itself. So ESG became a thing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Environmental, social, and governance.</p><p> SEIDES: Three things which may or may not have anything to do with each other.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Clearly.</p><p> SEIDES: You can go back and say, “Remember FANG?” And then Fang had two A&#39;s, and then it turned into FANMAG. So these names have a way of taking off. Back in the day —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: BRIC, remember BRIC.</p><p> SEIDES: BRIC and emerging markets, Brazil, Russia, India, China. So the problem with ESG in its first iteration was that the label that everyone ascribed to it wasn&#39;t anything anyone could understand.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s track that evolution. This all started with divesting South African investments with, I think it was Harvard actually, or Yale was one of the Ivies that the student population wanted the endowment out of that, which led to socially responsible investing, which led to impact investing. Like there have been a ton of names. ESG just seems to be a catch all umbrella.</p><p> What should it be called or should it be called anything?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I think it goes back to what we talked about at the onset about beliefs. Each institution has to decide how do they want to align their investing with the purpose of the institution? What are they trying to solve for? So lots of people want to solve for, call it sustainable investing. What does that mean?我不知道。 But the idea of an environment that humans can habit for centuries, seems like that resonates with people. So that leads to one set of sort of investment criteria that you could filter into your whole portfolio.</p><p> The S is really about diversity and that&#39;s important to a lot of people. Certainly in financial services, we recognize now that there are all these microaggressions that have been in place for decades. I&#39;m not sure how that turns into an investment strategy.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: See, I don&#39;t even think of it in those terms. I think of it as you want to avoid groupthink and if everybody went to the same undergrad, went to the same grad, went to the same training program, well, you&#39;re cranking out these automatons that are going to think, speak, and act similarly, and so the investment results will be similar, therefore subpar, so let&#39;s bring in different people from different backgrounds, different thought processes, different education, so that there is some robust diversity of thought.</p><p> I just don&#39;t, like the microaggression thing, I could care less about.</p><p> SEIDES: So the challenge is that the academic research shows that what you&#39;re trying to solve for is cognitive diversity.</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> SEIDES: Social diversity is a proxy for cognitive diversity.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Not a great one.</p><p> SEIDES: By the way, no, you could have people from all different races that think exactly the same way because they were educated at the same places.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: So the question is, if you care about improving your investment results from cognitive diversity, which we can all agree the research shows makes sense, is that a thing that you measure? Is that a thing that you evaluate? Like, how do you do that? So nobody really knows. And then governance, like, I&#39;m not sure I know of anyone, except for occasionally an activist investor as an opportunity set that is pro-poor governance.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Yeah, I can&#39;t really hear that anybody has been agitating for, “You need to make your governance worse.”</p><p> SEIDES: So what&#39;s evolved over the last couple of years is, starting with sort of Greta Thunberg, and then during COVID, when ESG took on this label, people created a whole bunch of products that nobody really understood what they were solving for. And so not that surprising, it hasn&#39;t really taken off in the way that a lot of people predicted four or five years ago.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But there&#39;s a ton of capital that has been allocated to, so let&#39;s work our way away from ESG. There are impact funds that go out of their way to make sure that half of their investments go to companies that are either managed by women or people of color, or are geographically away from New York, Boston, San Francisco, Silicon Valley, because the rest of the country has innovations and we&#39;ve been ignoring them.</p><p> And in fact, the competition in San Francisco and Silicon Valley is much more intense than Milwaukee or Orlando.</p><p> SEIDES: So I think that&#39;s right. The question is, what does a ton of capital mean? Right, in the scheme of things, The point I would make is that the amount of money that&#39;s gone into these different called diversifying strategies is much less than people thought it was going to be four or five years ago because it&#39;s all under this umbrella that each individual organization needs to figure out what do they care about and how do they want to deploy capital to meet that objective.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Don&#39;t some foundations have a sort of a checkbox approach? Hey, we want to give 5% of our alternative assets to funds run by women or funds run by minorities or LGBT, like down the list as a way of providing a little social diversity.</p><p> But again, the point you make is, is social diversity the same as cognitive diversity? Is it a good proxy?</p><p> SEIDES: They absolutely want to do that as long as those funds outperform.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s really interesting. So once the outperformance stops, we swap managers. That&#39;s really interesting.</p><p> Last question on ESG, certain folks have been saying, “Hey, you know, it works as a pretty good risk management filter. Boards that have 30, 40% women tend not to have the same sort of Me Too problems as a board that&#39;s all a whole bunch of old white guys. How do you respond to this is a risk management filter that allows us to identify the worst actors in corporate America?</p><p> SEIDES: I think that&#39;s a very reasonable way of looking at it. Again, depending on your investment strategy, are we talking about boards of stocks? What about in private markets? What about an early stage venture and a hedge fund? Like there&#39;s all different ways that you can think about integrating it and just like the problem with ESG, there&#39;s no one absolute solution that works for everything.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really quite fascinating.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk a little bit about capital allocators. What made you decide to play with this whole podcast thing?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I guess I was channeling my inner Barry Ritholtz some years ago. When I left Protege Partners, I wasn&#39;t sure what I would do, and I had picked up a bunch of, call it consulting or advisory relationships. And I had written that first book about hedge funds, which led me-</p><p> RITHOLTZ: In 2016, right?</p><p> SEIDES: In 2016.</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> SEIDES: Which led me to be on a couple of podcasts. And I woke up one day and said, “Huh, maybe I&#39;ll run around and talk to my old friends.”我不知道。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Dude, you&#39;re ruining my secret. It&#39;s the greatest gig, the easiest thing in the world, and now everybody&#39;s doing it. But for a while, it was my secret little garden that no one knew about.</p><p> SEIDES: And so I did that and I started a podcast called “Capital Allocators” and the idea was to be interviewing the people and make it be about the people, and then of course about investment strategies focused on the allocator CIO community and some of their favored money managers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And that&#39;s a rich, deep pool. People don&#39;t realize, you ever get the question, “Hey, are you worried you&#39;re going to run out of people?” I&#39;m like, “No, I got 10 million people to go. What, are you kidding me?”</p><p> SEIDES: There&#39;s never been a shortage of high quality people to have on. And so I started that six years ago, not knowing, certainly not thinking it would be a business. I used to joke, hey, Barry, we&#39;re going to have a conversation. Share it for free.” And just like the change bank from “Saturday Night Live, “We&#39;ll make it up in volume.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, right.</p><p> SEIDES: Like it was sort of a dot-com click business. And I just kept doing it for a number of years alongside of these other projects.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Which, by the way, something like 90% of the podcasts drop off within a year. They just, it&#39;s work, it&#39;s not easy.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, but it was just so much fun. And it was one of the things that —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Again, you&#39;re ruining my secret. It&#39;s endless fun, right? I mean, think about, I went through the list of some of the people you spoke with. You could see there is delight in the conversation you have with people.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. It&#39;s a version of what I did my whole career, right? I spent time interviewing money managers with a very, very different output mechanism. So in the past, I&#39;d have an interview with a manager and I would be evaluating them and I would mostly say no, but sometimes you&#39;d say, “Oh, what do I think of them?” And this is just, you have the same conversation. There&#39;s no evaluation. You get to be on everyone&#39;s team and then you share it with people. And what&#39;s happened over the years is it&#39;s become the largest podcast in institutional investing.</p><p> So that allocator community listens and people have incredible experiences when they come on. And it&#39;s just so rewarding. It&#39;s by far the most rewarding thing I&#39;ve done in my professional career.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I say to people, “This is the most fun I have all week.” And they look at me like, “Wait, what? You need to get a life.” I&#39;m like, “No, you don&#39;t understand.”</p><p>赛德斯：（笑）</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Is it the most fun you have each week when you speak to somebody?</p><p> SEIDES: Absolutely.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But first of all, my dirty little secret, and I don&#39;t know if this is yours, I don&#39;t care who&#39;s listening. I invite people that I want to sit down with for an hour or two and have this conversation. If someone listens, great, but I don&#39;t care.是的。 It&#39;s like, “No, no, I have an audience of one.这就是我。 It&#39;s my selfish indulgence.” “Oh, okay, other people have listened.” But when you&#39;re picking people who invite, how much of it is, “Oh, I really want to sit down and talk to that guy or that girl.”</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s all of it. I still and always will source all the guests myself.</p><p> We do get a lot of inbounds and we figured out ways of getting more people involved that I might not have known about. But it is entirely, “Hey, what do I think is interesting? “Who would I like to talk to?” And you go from there.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You focus primarily on the institutional side of things. How does that translate into who listens? Do you want a broader audience or do you like this somewhat narrow but incredibly deep and knowledgeable listenership?</p><p> What led you in that direction other than that&#39;s the world you came from?</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s mostly that and it goes to what you said, which is I love having these conversations and have never advertised on the podcast. I&#39;m sorry, I&#39;ve never advertised for the podcast other than a couple little experiments.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So do you promote the podcast? Other than going on other people&#39;s podcasts, how do you get to the point where people are listening other than the circle of institutional allocators?</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s been entirely organic. We&#39;ve done a few little experiments, promoting and advertising, none of it&#39;s worked. So I&#39;ve never really cared about it. It is kind of like what you said. I didn&#39;t think of it as a business when I started. I barely do now. And people have found it because it added value to their professional careers.</p><p> So most of that audience, I would say, as far as we can tell, a little less than half is the institutional allocator community. And that spans endowments, foundations. Where I came from, it spans sovereign wealth funds, pension funds, incredibly global. And that reach, which I&#39;m sure you know –</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It&#39;s hilarious.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s so much wider than I ever could have imagined existed.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Because the internet is totally global and I&#39;m sure you&#39;ve had this experience. I&#39;ve had guests say, I heard from a kid I went to camp with who now runs a fund in Hong Kong. I mean, but there&#39;s nothing local about a podcast. If it&#39;s on the internet, it&#39;s totally discoverable. I&#39;ve also had the same experience with half. If half are institutional allocators, who&#39;s the other half?</p><p> SEIDES: Most of it&#39;s money managers. So it&#39;s most of the people in the community.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: The people they&#39;re allocating to.</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s correct. And then there&#39;s this other, right? So you get notes from students, from friends who are outside. It&#39;s just entertainment.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: MBA professors, you hear from professors saying, “Hey, I love this interview. “I assigned this to the class.”</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, it&#39;s just fantastic.</p><p> So that&#39;s one of the fun things about it is you just, anyone can listen.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So curve ball question. What&#39;s your favorite podcast guest story that you can tell publicly? Because we all have great stories, some of which not really FCC approved.</p><p> SEIDES: There are one or two of those, but not that many. I think I would even go all the way back to my very first episode. So it was with Steve Galbraith, who we mentioned earlier with Jack Bogle. And it was just this idea, I knew Steve, I knew he had a great story, and I sat down and recorded it. And I couldn&#39;t find the recording on the recording device after we finished.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGH)</p><p> SEIDES: And it was so good, I just said, I can&#39;t wait to share this with people. And then I thought that that was the end of my podcast career after the first recording. And it took a good friend of mine, who&#39;s a technical whiz to figure out, which actually wasn&#39;t that hard, I just didn&#39;t know how to do it, to extract the conversation from the recording device.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I&#39;m going to share a similar story with you. So normally I&#39;m in the Bloomberg studios. I got an engineer, I got all the latest equipment. I have the easiest gig in podcast. I show up, I said, “Hey, print this out for me, off we go.” One about five years ago, I&#39;m planning a trip to Silicon Valley. I tee up two interviews in a day, Mark Andreessen of Andreessen Horowitz and Nobel Laureate Bill Sharpe. And by coincidence, I couldn&#39;t find a place to record the Bill Sharp interview, Andreessen said, “Oh, do it here. “You could use our podcast studios.” They were great. So I sit down with Bill, so I do Andreessen in the morning, right? In the afternoon is Bill Sharp, after lunch. I sit down, I have my device, which the engineer has taught me 47 times how to do, and I start the podcast with Bill Sharp, and maybe 90 seconds in, I notice I&#39;m not recording.</p><p> And I just have my stomach sinks. And I imagine spending an hour and a half with Bill Sharp and not having it record. So I&#39;m like, “Bill, I&#39;m not getting a good audio level. “Let&#39;s start this again.” So I hit it and now the red light&#39;s on, the view meter&#39;s going crazy, and I could see it&#39;s recording. I go, “Let&#39;s start over. “I think you were too soft.” And I just adjust it and we do the recording. And to me, that was the nightmare scenario of missing, God, Nobel Laureate, imagine that. So you found the Galbraith…</p><p> SEIDES: Found the recording, went out, and the rest is history.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So that&#39;s really interesting. So we only have you for so much time, and I appreciate you tolerating my nonsense.</p><p> Let&#39;s jump to my favorite questions that I ask all of my guests, some of which I think I&#39;m ready to retire. Probably the first one I&#39;m ready to retire, which is a post-lockdown question. I was asking people, hey, what are you streaming? What&#39;s keeping you entertained during lockdown?</p><p> Let&#39;s see if you have an answer to that. What have you been watching that&#39;s interesting?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I&#39;m a Ted Lasso guy, and I&#39;ve watched the finale of the last season three times.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I thought that was unfairly slagged. It was really good.</p><p> SEIDES: It was really good. So in addition to that, I had on the show last year a guy named Brent Montgomery, and Brent&#39;s a TV producer. He created Pawn Stars and Duck Dynasty. His latest show is called The King of Collectibles.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: And it&#39;s Pawn Stars meets sports. The guy named Ken Golden, who&#39;s one of the largest sports collectibles dealers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: And it is so, so good.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Do you get into the massive amount of counterfeit crap that&#39;s in that space at all? Because I would, of all the junk I buy, sports collectibles is the last thing in the world I would ever risk a penny on. I&#39;m convinced there&#39;s some kid in some sweatshop in a basement signing Michael Jordan&#39;s name over and over again.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, they do show how they go through the authentication process, at least with this one very high quality dealer.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, I mean, I&#39;m sure there are ways to authenticate it, but every time I look at something on eBay, I just kind of like look it and go, no way.</p><p> SEIDES: This has, you know, it has Mike Tyson on it, it has all these incredible athletes and entertainers that get involved with this guy. It&#39;s a fantastic show.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really, that sounds really, really interesting.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk about books. You&#39;ve written two of them. What are some of the favorite books that you&#39;ve read and what are you reading currently?</p><p> SEIDES: This year, the favorite book I&#39;ve read is “Unreasonable Hospitality.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I just got that book. Somebody recommended it. It looks fascinating.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s by Will Guidara, who&#39;s one of the founders of Eleven Madison, Danny Meyer&#39;s partner, and really describes in excruciating, thoughtful detail what it takes to be a creative customer, a customer-focused organization. It&#39;s a phenomenal book.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: For a long time, Eleven Madison was just, you know, Michelin rated, everything else. It was spectacular.</p><p> SEIDES: So that&#39;s my favorite one this year. The one I&#39;ve been reading most recently, which has been a long project before I go to bed, and it&#39;s a 10-year-old book, is Bill Simmons&#39; “Book of Basketball.”</p><p> So Bill Simmons wrote a book that ranked the top 100 basketball players, as again, 10 years ago, of all time, using both stats and his incredible knowledge and judgment, and it is addictive and incredibly fun.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So spoiler, was it Jordan or LeBron? Who does he rank as number one?</p><p> SEIDES: I&#39;m only up to 25, which is Bill Walton.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So you don&#39;t know.</p><p> SEIDES: I don&#39;t know yet.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And you know, 10 years ago, was Curry really on the list?</p><p> SEIDES: So early on in the book, he had this tiered system and he talked about the players that weren&#39;t yet on it. And Curry was mentioned as one he didn&#39;t think would get onto the list in a future edition.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Hilarious, right? And now he&#39;s probably top 10, right? Is that a fair statement?</p><p> Last two questions. What sort of advice would you give to a recent college graduate interested in a career in either alternative investments, allocation, anything finance related?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, the general advice I give, and I heard it phrased beautifully by a guy named Eric Resnick, who runs the largest private equity firm for travel and leisure, was recently on our show. He was told early on, combine your vocation with your avocation, which is just a thoughtful way of saying, do what you love.</p><p> I think that&#39;s general.</p><p> The problem with finance and alternative investments I would give advice that Howard Marks gives, which is if you want to have a great career in this space, start 30 years ago.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s great. I love Howard.</p><p> And our final question, what do you know about the world of investing today? You wish you knew 25, 30 years ago when you were first getting started.</p><p> SEIDES: I think the importance of people. We&#39;re talking about governance and decision-making and it was something that David Swensen taught me early on. But you have to go through people in difficult times, experiencing good and bad behavior in those times to really understand that ultimately active management is a people business.</p><p> And yes, you have to have all the investment discipline and all the rigor that goes into that, but they are human beings that are making decisions and that evaluating people as a frame for how you think about where you want to allocate your capital is probably the single most important thing you can do.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really fascinating stuff, Ted. Thank you for being so generous with your time.</p><p> We have been speaking with Ted Seides. He is the founder of Capital Allocator and the author of “Capital Allocators, How the World&#39;s Elite Money Managers Lead and Invest” and the host of the “Capital Allocators” podcast.</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 498 podcasts we&#39;ve done over the past eight years. You can find those at iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, wherever you find your favorite podcast. Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me o